03696nam a22006855i 9780813549910DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20122012nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2011023487  a97808135499107 a10.36019/97808135499102doi  a(DE-B1597)530297  a(OCoLC)811641689  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aPN56.W6bM35 2012 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a809/.9335222231 aManganelli, Kimberly Snyder, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTransatlantic Spectacles of Race :bThe Tragic Mulatta and the Tragic Muse /cKimberly Snyder Manganelli. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b13 photogrpahs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe American Literatures Initiative0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe tragic mulatta was a stock figure in nineteenth-century American literature, an attractive mixed-race woman who became a casualty of the color line. The tragic muse was an equally familiar figure in Victorian British culture, an exotic and alluring Jewish actress whose profession placed her alongside the “fallen woman.” In Transatlantic Spectacles of Race, Kimberly Manganelli argues that the tragic mulatta and tragic muse, who have heretofore been read separately, must be understood as two sides of the same phenomenon. In both cases, the eroticized and racialized female body is put on public display, as a highly enticing commodity in the nineteenth-century marketplace. Tracing these figures through American, British, and French literature and culture, Manganelli constructs a host of surprising literary genealogies, from Zelica to Daniel Deronda, from Uncle Tom’s Cabin to Lady Audley’s Secret. Bringing together an impressive array of cultural texts that includes novels, melodramas, travel narratives, diaries, and illustrations, Transatlantic Spectacles of Race reveals the value of transcending literary, national, and racial boundaries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aRace in literature. 0aRacially mixed women in literature. 0aTragic, The, in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081354991040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813549910423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780813549910/original  a978-3-11-068861-0  Rutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK